            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~Cheeko" class="author" title="author name and user ID">Cheeko (165493) </a> | about 3 years ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=2274044&cid=36585216">(#36585216)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_36585216" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="2" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body"><p>And to the points made in the dissent in this case, at least they were well thought out and reasonable.  I think the court made the right call, but I did find it interesting in Thomas' argument about how even in speech matters the parent is still the intermediary, I can say what I want, but the parent has control over what their children can here.  I don't find this totally unreasonable of a concept.</p><p>My issue with the law was that government would have to make a determination of what content meets a violent standard and that is definitely against the free speech framework.  Its also a slipper slope in terms of ever changing social standards.</p><p>I think in this case the 2 dissenting votes had more to do with interpretation of the role of the parent in the law as it was structured, versus the role of government in the law.</p></div>
