<article class="comment-article com-show" id="tree_36584974" data-cid="36584974">
    <div id="comment_36584974">
        <header data-points="4" data-reason="Insightful">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="How... Ironic."><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>How... Ironic.<span> (4, Insightful)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~fuzzyfuzzyfungus" class="author" title="author name and user ID">fuzzyfuzzyfungus (1223518) </a> | about 3 years ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=2274044&cid=36584974">(#36584974)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_36584974" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="4" data-reason="Insightful">
            <div class="comment-body">"
 JUSTICE THOMAS, dissenting. <br> <br>
The Court&rsquo;s decision today  does not comport with the
original public understanding of  the First  Amendment.
The majority strikes down, as facially unconstitutional, a
state law that prohibits the direct sale or rental of certain
video games to minors because the law &ldquo;abridg[es] the
freedom of speech.&rdquo;  U. S. Const.,  Amdt. 1.   But I do not
think the First Amendment stretches that far.  <br> <br>The practices and beliefs of the founding generation establish that
&ldquo;the freedom of speech,&rdquo; as originally understood, does not
include a right to speak to minors (or a right of minors to
access speech) without going through the minors&rsquo; parents
or guardians.   I would hold that the law at issue  is not
facially unconstitutional under the First Amendment, and
reverse and remand for further proceedings."<br> <br>

Justice Thomas should, perhaps, stop to consider that the "practices and beliefs of the founding generation" establish a number of other <em>interesting</em> boundaries to the distribution of various freedoms...</div>
            <footer class="comment-footer" id="comment_footer_36584974">
